President Donald Trump has proclaimed April 2017 as National Sexual Assault Awareness and Prevention Month. In his proclamation, he emphasizes the belief that every person has unique and infinite value and that their inherent dignity should never be violated. He acknowledges the prevalence of sexual assault in the United States, with over 300,000 instances reported annually. The President expresses his commitment to reducing and ending sexual violence through meaningful strategies, including increasing awareness, creating systems to protect vulnerable groups, and sharing successful prevention strategies. He directs the Department of Justice and the Department of Health and Human Services to do everything in their power to protect women, children, and men from sexual violence. The President also highlights the importance of prevention, such as changing social norms and engaging young people and men as allies in preventing sexual and relationship violence. He calls for a culture of respect and appreciation for the dignity of every human being and urges all Americans, organizations, and communities to support survivors of sexual assault and work together to prevent these crimes.